All Implemented Interfaces:
ICdmBase, ILoadableTerm, Serializable, Comparable<TypeDesignationStatus>
public class TypeDesignationStatus
extends OrderedTermBase<TypeDesignationStatus>

The class representing status (categories) of specimen type designations for a taxon name or a set of them. Within this set basionyms or replaced synonyms, in case of reclassifications, will be here referred as "type-bringing" taxon names.

The different status indicate whether the specimens used as types in a designation are duplicates, replacements, related specimens etc.

A standard (ordered) list of type designation status instances will be automatically created as the project starts. But this class allows to extend this standard list by creating new instances of additional type designation status if needed.

This class corresponds to:

  • NomencalturalTypeTypeTerm according to the TDWG ontology
  • NomenclaturalTypeStatusOfUnitsEnum according to the TCS

Version:
1.0

isLectotype

public boolean isLectotype()
Returns the boolean value indicating whether this type designation status is itself "lectotype" or a kind of "lectotype" (true) or not (false). Returns false if this type designation status is null.
A lectotype is a specimen or illustration designated as the nomenclatural type, when no holotype was indicated at the time of publication of the "type-bringing" taxon name, when the holotype is found to be assigned to taxon names belonging to more than one homotypical group, or as long as it is missing.

See Also:
LECTOTYPE(), HOLOTYPE(), DefinedTermBase.getKindOf()

HOLOTYPE

public static final TypeDesignationStatus HOLOTYPE()
Returns the "holotype" designation status. A holotype of a set of names is the one specimen or illustration designated as the nomenclatural type by the author of the "type-bringing" taxon name (or by the author of a later validated "invalid" taxon name).

See Also:
NameRelationshipType.VALIDATED_BY_NAME()

LECTOTYPE

public static final TypeDesignationStatus LECTOTYPE()
Returns the "lectotype" designation status. A lectotype is a specimen or illustration designated as the nomenclatural type, when no holotype was indicated at the time of publication of the "type-bringing" taxon name, when the holotype is found to to be assigned to taxon names belonging to more than one homotypical group, or as long as it is missing.

See Also:
HOLOTYPE()

NEOTYPE

public static final TypeDesignationStatus NEOTYPE()
Returns the "neotype" designation status. A neotype is a specimen or illustration selected to serve as nomenclatural type as long as all of the material on which the "type-bringing" taxon name was based is missing.

See Also:
HOLOTYPE()

EPITYPE

public static final TypeDesignationStatus EPITYPE()
Returns the "epitype" designation status. An epitype is a specimen or illustration selected to serve as an interpretative type when the holotype, lectotype or previously designated neotype, or all original material associated with the validly published "type-bringing" taxon name, is demonstrably ambiguous and cannot be critically identified for purposes of the precise application of the taxon name. When an epitype is designated, the holotype, lectotype or neotype that the epitype supports must be explicitly cited.

See Also:
HOLOTYPE(), LECTOTYPE(), NEOTYPE()

ISOTYPE

public static final TypeDesignationStatus ISOTYPE()
Returns the "isotype" designation status. An isotype is any duplicate of the holotype; it is always a specimen.

See Also:
HOLOTYPE()

SYNTYPE

public static final TypeDesignationStatus SYNTYPE()
Returns the "syntype" designation status. A syntype is any one of two or more specimens cited in the protologue of the "type-bringing" taxon name when no holotype was designated, or any one of two or more specimens simultaneously designated as types.

See Also:
HOLOTYPE()

PARATYPE

public static final TypeDesignationStatus PARATYPE()
Returns the "paratype" designation status. A paratype is a specimen cited in the protologue of the "type-bringing" taxon name that is neither the holotype nor an isotype, nor one of the syntypes if two or more specimens were simultaneously designated as types.

See Also:
HOLOTYPE(), ISOTYPE(), SYNTYPE()

ISOLECTOTYPE

Returns the "isolectotype" designation status. An isolectotype is any duplicate of the lectotype; it is always a specimen.

LECTOTYPE()

PARANEOTYPE

public static final TypeDesignationStatus PARANEOTYPE()
Returns the "paraneotype" designation status. A paraneotype is a specimen, cited when selecting a neotype, other than the neotype itself. Also called "neoparatype" in zoology.

See Also:
NEOTYPE()

SECOND_STEP_LECTOTYPE

public static final TypeDesignationStatus SECOND_STEP_LECTOTYPE()
Returns the "second step lectotype" designation status. A second step lectotype is a specimen or illustration, designated as lectotype in order to substitute another already existing lectotype.

See Also:
LECTOTYPE()

LECTOTYPE()

PARALECTOTYPE

public static final TypeDesignationStatus PARALECTOTYPE()
Returns the "paralectotype" designation status. A paralectotype is a specimen, cited when designating a lectotype, other than the lectotype itself. Also called "lectoparatype" in zoology.

See Also:
LECTOTYPE()

ISOEPITYPE

ICONOTYPE

public static final TypeDesignationStatus ICONOTYPE()
Returns the "iconotype" designation status. An iconotype is a holotype or a lectotype that is a drawing and not a specimen.

See Also:
HOLOTYPE(), LECTOTYPE()

Returns the "iconotype" designation status. An iconotype is a holotype or a lectotype that is a photograph and not a specimen.
